  "eprint": {
    "title": "Unifying Generic Group Models",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Ueli Maurer",
        "email": "zhu@inf",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Christopher Portmann",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Jiamin Zhu",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "To prove computational complexity lower bounds in cryp-\ntography, one often resorts to so-called generic models of computation.\nFor example, a generic algorithm for the discrete logarithm is one which\nworks independently from the group representation—and thus works\ngenerically for all group representations. There are a multitude of different\nmodels in the literature making comparing different results—and\neven matching lower and upper bounds proven in different models—\nrather difficult.\nIn this work we view a model as a set of games with the same type of\ninteractions. Using a standard notion of reduction between two games,\nwe establish a hierarchy between models. Different models may now be\nclassified as weaker and stronger if a reduction between them exists. We\npropose different extensions of the generic group model with different\nqueries, explicitly capturing different information that an algorithm may\nneed to exploit.\nFinally, we use the hierarchy between these models to systematically\ncompare and improve the results in the literature. First we strengthen\nthe model in which the baby-step giant-step algorithm is proven and\nweaken the model in which the matching lower bound is proven. We\nthen analyse the discrete logarithm with preprocessing. Upper and lower\nbounds have been proven in the literature in mismatching models. We\nweaken the model of the lower bound and strengthen the model of the\nupper bound to close the gap between the two.",
    "keywords": [
      "Generic Group Model",
      "prepreocessing",
      "non-uniform"
    ],
    "category": "Foundations",
    "publication_info": "Preprint. MINOR revision.",
    "last_updated": "2020-08-26",
